                        Political Adviser in Korea (
                        Langdon
                    )Repeated to Moscow as telegram No.
                        963.</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1946v08</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d390</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">390</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1946-05-24T13:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1946-05-24T13:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-05-24T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-05-24T13:00:00-05:00" n="390" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d390">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 PW/5–2246: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Political Adviser in Korea</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Langdon</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="44" xml:id="d390fn1">Repeated to Moscow as telegram No.
                        963.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">us urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-05-24T14:00:00-04:00">May 24, 1946—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>77. For Ambassador Pauley. As you have seen from Department’s telegram to Moscow
                    repeated to Seoul as no. 76, May 22,<note n="45" xml:id="d390fn2">See footnote
                        43, above.</note> I have again asked the Soviet Government to grant
                    necessary authority for your Mission to proceed to northern Korea. Since it
                    appears that the size of your staff is one of the principal obstacles in
                    obtaining permission I hope you will make every effort to reduce the number to a
                    minimum adequate to your purposes.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Byrnes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
